Task 1
Create a variable quote and assign it the following value:
'A good programmer is someone who always looks both ways before crossing a one-way street'

Task 2
Display the text written in uppercase letters only.

Task 3
Display the text written in lowercase letters only.

Task 4
Check whether the text ends with the word 'street'.

Task 5
Check whether the text is written in uppercase letters.

Task 6
Check whether the text converted to uppercase is written in uppercase letters
(use method chaining).

Task 7
Find the position (counting from zero) where the word (substring) 'one' appears in the text.

Task 8
Replace the word (substring) 'one' with '1'.

Task 9
Replace the word (substring) 'one' with '1' and the word 'both' with '2'.

Task 10
Split the string into smaller strings using a space as the separator.

Task 11
Check whether the string is:

a number,

a decimal number,

a string containing only letters,

a string containing letters and digits.

Explanation

In Task 11, you will get four False values.
The last two results may be especially surprising.

The string contains spaces and consists of multiple words, which is why it is neither an alphabetic string nor an alphanumeric string.